<subSubSection id="9521E251DEC40497C9E5105539A1E46E" pageId="18" pageNumber="25" type="comments">
<paragraph id="5946D78F05D5BB9DA5EB295D08456C1A" pageId="18" pageNumber="25">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="23004BB9429A886B1AA06B6F6AA73CCE" pageId="18" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicName id="6B286CB7CF3E989DE45A6624B80E2981" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Panops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Panops austrae" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="austrae">Panops austrae</taxonomicName>
is a large, metallic coloured species similar to 
<taxonomicName id="6077F72FB537B35150C2D8D362BC90B4" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Panops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Panops jade" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jade">Panops jade</taxonomicName>
sp. n. and 
<taxonomicName id="380D9BF0DB0EF1E7793D86747334C039" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Panops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Panops schlingeri" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schlingeri">Panops schlingeri</taxonomicName>
sp. n. It is easily distinguished from these species by the longer proboscis and dense white thoracic pile. This species is known from remote, arid regions of the Northern Territory and Western Australia.
</paragraph>
